          "name": "How is 194Q calculated with an example?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Section 194Q requires a buyer whose turnover exceeded Rs 10 crore in the preceding financial year to deduct 0.1 percent on the value of goods purchased from a resident seller above Rs 50 lakh in a year. On purchases of Rs 80 lakh from one supplier, tax applies to Rs 30 lakh, giving Rs 3,000. Where the seller has no PAN the rate rises to 5 percent."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between Section 194Q and Section 206C(1H)?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Section 194Q puts the obligation on the buyer to deduct TDS on purchases of goods, while Section 206C(1H) put it on the seller to collect TCS on sales. Both used the same Rs 50 lakh threshold and 0.1 percent rate, and where both could apply, the buyer's deduction under Section 194Q took precedence. The TCS provision has since been withdrawn."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Where is TDS 194Q not applicable?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "It does not apply where the seller is a non-resident, where the goods are imported, where the buyer's turnover did not cross Rs 10 crore in the preceding year, or in the first year of a new business that has no preceding turnover. It also steps aside when tax is deductible under another provision or collectible under Section 206C other than sub-section (1H)."
          }
        }
